english:
  title: Inscription for the Bell of Wongyaksa Temple, with Preface
  author: Choi Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven shakes ten thousand things with thunder. Buddha awakens the multitude with a bell. The mysterious workings know no fixed form, yet without the thunder of Great Strength, how could motion stir in all beings? True teaching has no boundary, yet without the sound of Great Resonance, how could the great dream be awakened?

    Thus we know: to stir the great cosmos and let sound flow through the six directions—nothing surpasses the voice in swiftness, and nothing equals metal in spreading its echo. The bell's purpose is indeed vast!

    Humbly I reflect: Our ruler, bearing Heaven's mandate and walking the Way, majestic in virtue and mighty in arms, ascends to the imperial throne and opens the cosmos. He molds the virtues of ancient sage-kings, harmonizes chaos and order, and through transformative grace raises all to flourishing. Yet his heart, compassionate toward all, yearns still to save the suffering. In the tenth year of his reign, the Year of the Tiger bringing the Cycle of Metal and Fire, he commands the great monastery Wongyaksa be built in the capital. There, fifty thousand pounds of refined metal are smelted and cast into a great bell, hung in the Tower of Cloud and Thunder—a radiant vessel of the Law.

    Balancing yin and yang, fire gods labor at their task, wind deities exert their strength. A hundred spirits answer together, and within mere days, this mighty work is complete. Bound with sturdy ropes, suspended on wooden frames, it stands ready. When struck once, it thunders; its clear voice vibrates through the nine heavens; its awesome resonance echoes through the three realms.

    Four kinds of beings hold their breath. All creatures listen intently. Not only the wise, hearing sound and understanding reception, observing reception and grasping the Law—stirring themselves to brave and diligent practice—but even the greedy and deluded awaken remorse and turn toward goodness; the deaf and blind are moved and find their way. The mind's source becomes naturally pure. The waves of consciousness flow gently. All reaches high to the peak of existence and low to the edge of emptiness. Celestial immortals in flight, spirits of land and sea—all dispel the darkness of ignorance, wash away the dust of delusion, cleanse the flaws of countless ages, and lighten the suffering of the long night.

    Thus the Buddha employs the vessel of the Law to broadcast the voice of dharma, spreading compassion and drawing forth compassionate intention—nothing surpasses the bell. And our ruler, embodying supreme compassion to save all beings, transmitting the Teaching in its image form, illuminating the mysterious Way to shine through the hidden and manifest realms, purifying all within the four seas—all this depends eternally on this bell.

    Alas, our ruler's mind is the Buddha's mind! Where mind and transformation dwell, it sounds without sounding. Where mind and transformation do not dwell, it sounds yet does not sound. The bell sounds through transformation; transformation flows through the bell. Yet all dharmas return to one mind. How could this be mere chance?

    I, your servant Hang, humbly bow and present this inscription:

    The Great Hero, the Great Way, vastness without measure,
    Great Compassion, Great Sorrow, saving the cosmos entire—
    One sound in four seasons opens heaven and earth.
    Its vast echo spans ten thousand ages, yet remains perfectly natural.

    How many years since the sacred Teaching flowed eastward?
    Our sage-king now uniquely transmits the heart.
    How could salvation exclude or favor any?
    All deliverance must depend upon the Golden Sage.

    Unfolding the mysterious design, opening the field of blessing,
    The grand structure towers, supporting heaven's vault.
    All spirits rush forward; the furnace burns bright,
    Purple flames reach the sky; the rainbow spans the night.

    On mighty pillars a thousand-pound bell suspends.
    Mirroring celestial forms—void yet perfect and round,
    Harmouring vast strength, it releases its sound in time.
    Suddenly the thunderbolt crashes on the hilltop;
    One strike awakens ten thousand towns from slumber.

    Driving away Mara's hosts, summoning celestial sages,
    Dragons and worthies of the ten directions gather in reverence.
    Hearing this, they forge anew the path of diligent practice;
    All suffering from flames and heat is instantly soothed—
    Just as this clear, cold pool washes one clean.

    Grand and fine, each tone responds to every strike,
    Good roots are planted, evil connections severed.
    The dharma drum and dharma trumpet move as one,
    Supernal powers and subtle marvels find no equal.

    Our ruler and the Buddha—their hearts are one,
    Bright as the peak of Sumeru mountain.
    The dharma voice thunders greatly, filling heaven and earth,
    Like the dust of the Ganges, enduring eternally.
  footnotes:
    - The 'six directions' (육허) refers to the six spatial realms—four cardinal directions, up, and down—a traditional Buddhist cosmological framework.
    - The 'Year of the Tiger bringing the Cycle of Metal and Fire' (용집 갑신년) refers to a specific calendar year in Korean history, marking the tenth year of the ruler's reign.
    - Mara (파순) is a figure in Buddhist mythology representing delusion and obstacle to enlightenment.
    - '''The Golden Sage'' refers to Buddha, traditionally depicted as golden in Buddhist iconography.'
    - The 'dharma drum' and 'dharma trumpet' are ritual instruments in Buddhism representing the proclamation of the teaching.
